  "prompt": "How do you treat poison ivy in your mouth? What are some risks?",
  "response": "Exposure to poison ivy in the mouth can be concerning, as it may cause irritation, swelling, and discomfort due to the plant's oily resin called **urushiol**, which triggers an allergic reaction. Here\u2019s how to treat it and understand the associated risks:\n\n### Immediate Steps to Take:\n1. **Rinse Thoroughly**: Gently rinse your mouth with cool water to remove any plant residue. Avoid swallowing the water.\n2. **Drink Water**: Sip water to help dilute any remaining urushiol.\n3. **Avoid Spreading**: Do not touch your face, lips, or other parts of your body to prevent spreading the oil.\n4. **Avoid Scrubbing**: Do not scrub the affected area, as this can worsen irritation.\n\n### Medical Treatment:\n1. **Antihistamines**: Over-the-counter antihistamines (e.g., diphenhydramine) can help reduce itching and swelling.\n2. **Topical Treatments**: For lips or external mouth areas, apply calamine lotion or hydrocortisone cream.\n3. **Oral Steroids**: In severe cases, a doctor may prescribe oral steroids to reduce inflammation.\n4. **Medical Evaluation**: Seek medical attention if symptoms are severe, such as difficulty breathing, swallowing, or severe swelling.\n\n### Risks and Complications:\n1. **Swelling**: Swelling in the mouth or throat can make breathing or swallowing difficult, which is a medical emergency.\n2. **Infection**: Scratching or irritation can increase the risk of secondary infections.\n3. **Allergic Reaction**: Some individuals may have a more severe allergic reaction, requiring immediate medical care.\n4. **Ingestion**: If urushiol is swallowed, it can irritate the digestive tract, though this is rare.\n\n### Prevention:\n- Avoid handling poison ivy or any part of the plant.\n- Wash hands and any exposed areas thoroughly after potential contact.\n- Be cautious when foraging or eating wild plants.\n\nIf symptoms persist or worsen, consult a healthcare professional promptly.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
